Step 2: List the outcomes. Label the two orange balls as O₁ and O₂, and the two blue balls as B₁ and B₂. The possible pairs are:
 • {O₁, O₂}
 • {O₁, B₁}
 • {O₁, B₂}
 • {O₂, B₁}
 • {O₂, B₂}
 • {B₁, B₂}

Step 3: Incorporate the given condition that at least one ball is orange. This condition eliminates the pair {B₁, B₂}. Therefore, only 5 outcomes remain.

Step 4: Identify the outcome where both balls are orange. Only one outcome, {O₁, O₂}, meets this criterion.

Step 5: Calculate the probability. With 1 favorable outcome out of 5 possible outcomes, the probability that both balls are orange given that at least one is orange is 1/5.

